Image-based Change Estimation (ICE) Summary for Maine, 2015 to 2018

Date: April 07, 2023

Overview

The Image-based Change Estimation (ICE) project from the USDA Forest Service, Forest Inventory and Analysis (FIA) Program provides information about land use and land cover composition and the causes of landscape changes. The ICE protocol is a relatively quick and simple, image-based approach of producing reliable estimates of land cover and land use change for a population. Data are collected using multi-date image interpretation of sample plot locations. The plot design used for this project consists of a plot center and a 144-foot radius plot.

ICE data for land use, land cover, and agent of change were collected for the population of Maine, on all lands. To determine and analyze land use, land cover, and agent of change for Maine, National Agriculture Imagery Program (NAIP) imagery was interpreted from 2015 and 2018. Estimates were generated using the FIESTA R Package (Frescino et al.2023).

Over the analysis period (2015 and 2018), Forest land use in Maine decreased by 0.080%, from 84.742%(+/-0.543 SE) in 2015 to 84.674%(+/-0.544 SE) in 2018; this is an average annual change of 0.023% (+/-0.009 SE). Tree land cover in Maine decreased by 1.769%, from 78.438%(+/-0.533 SE) in 2015 to 77.050%(+/-0.544 SE) in 2018; this is an average annual change of 0.463% (+/-0.048 SE).


Land Use

Land use describes the management and modification of the land. Figure 1 shows the estimated land use change for Maine between 2015 and 2018 among all land use classes. This provides information on transitional changes across the state by category. Here, we see the highest change in land use in Maine between 2015 and 2018 was Forest to Cultural, with an estimated 0.04% (0.02 SE). The orange cells represent transitions where change occurred.

Figure 1: Estimated percent land use for Maine from 2015 to 2018, with standard error values in parentheses.*Less than 0.005%.


Net change shows the overall change across Maine. Figure 2 presents the net land use change among all classes for Maine (2015 to 2018). Here, the blue bars reflect a positive change and the red bars reflect a negative change. The largest net gain in Maine was Cultural land use with 0.054% (0.023 SE). The largest net loss in Maine was Forest land use with -0.068% (0.027 SE). Figure 3 focuses on forest land use change only showing a gain of 0.005 (0.003% SE) and loss of 0.073% (0.027 SE).

Figure 2: Estimated percent net land use change for Maine for all classes from 2015 to 2018. Class names in gray text were not captured by the sample in Maine. Error bars represent one standard error (upper limit).

Figure 3: Estimated percent of Maines area that experienced Forest land use gain (left bar) and loss (right bar) between 2015 and 2018. Error bars represent one standard error (upper limit).



Land Cover

Land cover describes the physical land type observed on the ground. Figure 4 shows the estimated land cover change for Maine between 2015 and 2018 among all land cover classes. This provides information on transitional changes across the state by category. Here, we see the highest change in land cover in Maine between 2015 and 2018 was Tree - Live to Other Vegetation, with an estimated 1.36% (0.12 SE). The orange cells represent transitions where change occurred.

Figure 4: Estimated land cover change for Maine 2015 to 2018, with standard error values in parentheses.*Less than 0.005%.


Figure 5 presents the net land cover change among all classes for Maine (2015 to 2018). Again, the blue bars reflect a positive change and the red bars reflect a negative change. The largest net gain in Maine was Other Vegetation land cover with 1.119% (0.148 SE). The largest net loss in Maine was Tree - Live land cover with -1.388% (0.143 SE). Figure 6 focuses on tree (live and dead standing) cover change only, with a gain of 0.27 (0.058% SE) and loss of 1.599% (0.129 SE).

Figure 5: Estimated percent net land cover change for Maine for all classes from 2015 to 2018. Class names in gray text were not captured by the sample in Maine. Error bars represent upper 95% confidence interval.

Figure 6: Estimated percent of Maines area that experienced tree (live and standing dead) cover gain (left bar) and loss (right bar) between 2015 and 2018. Error bars represent one standard error (upper limit).



Agent of Change

Figure 7 displays the percent change by agent of change for Maine from 2015 to 2018. The largest agent of change across Maine was Harvest with 5.54% (0.38 SE) change in percentage points.

Figure 7: Estimated percent area of Maine that changed between 2015 and 2018 by agent of change, on all lands. Error bars represent one standard error (upper limit).



Land Use and Land Cover

Now, lets look at land cover and land use together for Maine, 2018. Figure 8 shows percent of land cover (X axis) within land use classes (Y axis), while figure 9 shows percent land use (X axis) within land cover classes (Y axis) across Maine. In Figure 8 we see the largest amount of land cover within Forest land use is Tree - Live with 89.7% cover, followed by Other Vegetation with 6.7% cover. Similarly, Forest is the largest land use within the Tree - Live land cover with 98.6% cover, followed by Cultural* with 0.9% cover (Figure 9).

Figure 8: The percent of Maine land cover (X axis) within different land use classes (Y axis) in 2018. Lighter shaded cells represent higher percentage of land cover within a given land use.


Figure 9: The percent of Maine land use (X axis) within different land cover classes (Y axis) in 2018. Lighter shaded cells represent higher percentage of land use within a given land cover.



Quality Assessment and Quality Control (QAQC) report

A quality assessment and quality control (QAQC) report was generated for Maine for 2015 to 2018 that compares agreement between original photo interpretations and blind re-interpretations by the same interpreter on the same plot (self checks), and also to blind interpretations made by another interpreter on the same plots (cross checks). The results are outlined below.

For presence of change, agreement was % in cross checks
For land use 1 and 2, agreement was % in cross checks
For land cover 1 and 2, agreement was % in cross checks
For change agent, agreement was % in cross checks

For more information on the QAQC analysis, reference ICE_Maine_2015_2018_QAQC.xlsx



Glossary

Agent of Change: Interpreted for each point that experienced change between the assessed time periods. Note: seasonal and expected changes, such as Crop Rotation and High Water, may be collected by interpreters but are not included in the change estimates reported.

Land Cover: Assessed at each of the sample points to determine what type of cover is present at the sample point. No MMU is required for land cover.

Land Use: Assessed at each of the sample points to determine what type of use is present. For land use, a minimum mapping unit (MMU) of 1.0 acres in size and greater than 120 feet wide must be met in order for select LUs to be recorded for each point.
